        {
          "DOI": "10.36227/techrxiv.172953448.85699324/v1",
          "URL": "https://doi.org/10.36227/techrxiv.172953448.85699324/v1",
          "abstract": "<jats:p>Deep supervised learning has revolutionized medical image segmentation although its success heavily relies on the availability of large volumes of training data with high-quality annotations. Self-supervised learning (SSL) methods have been recently introduced to address the annotation starving problem. In this paper, we report a general, scalable framework that combines contrastive and generative SSL methods to effectively learn robust and task-specific representations from large unannotated medical image datasets. Specifically, the SSL strategy is based on restoring transformed sub-volume images and contrasting the representations of paired transformed sub-volume images. By fine-tuning the pre-trained encoder-decoder network on small annotated medical image datasets, improved segmentation performance is efficiently achieved. The performance of our method was evaluated on two X-ray computed tomography (CT) image segmentation tasks and achieved better than state-of-theart results when 3D-segmenting a) psoas muscles in 60 torso CT images, and b) 20 thoracic organs at risk in a public SegTHOR dataset, demonstrating the effectiveness and broad applicability of our novel framework.</jats:p>",
